    Hi NorseHorse,<br>
    <br>
    Thanks for the quick fixes =E2=80=94 everything I ran into is sorted =
now.<br>
    <br>
    The "carry both" idea works well. It's nice just using whichever one
    my client makes easy. The only small thing: when a message carries
    multiple attachments, the inline block and the attachments don't
    line up as cleanly in the layout =E2=80=94 but it's really not a big =
deal.<br>
    <br>
    Honestly, I've never actually seen what an encrypted email with
    multiple attachments looks like on your device when it's sent from
    my Thunderbird =E2=80=94 same as the earlier ones I sent you. Could y=
ou send
    me a screenshot sometime (or whatever's easy) =E2=80=94 or just let m=
e know,
    does the attachment list look messy on your end?<br>
    <br>
    I've started on the translation. I'll reach out the moment it's
    done, or sooner if I hit any questions.<br>
    <br>
    Thanks again,<br>
    FHYQ
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <p><br>
    </p>
    On 6/27/2026 6:35 AM, NorseHorse wrote:<br>
    <blockquote type=3D"cite">This is great feedback, thank you. A couple=

      of the things you flagged we have already traced, and you were
      right on both counts.<br>
      <br>
      Signing first, since you nailed it. The "This isn't the hardware
      key for this signing key" failure is exactly the mismatch you
      described, and it is the same one from the link bug, just in the
      signing path this time. The signing check is comparing your card's
      signing slot against your primary key's fingerprint (746017E1)
      instead of the on-card signing subkey (D21621F3), so for an
      offline-primary layout it can never match. The link fix did not
      carry over to signing. The fix is the same shape as before, match
      the card's signing slot against the key's subkeys, and that is
      what I will do.<br>
      <br>
      The PIN duration issue is also confirmed, and it is what you
      suspected, not just the display. When you change the duration, the
      already-remembered PIN keeps its old expiry until the next decrypt
      re-applies the new setting. The cause is that the expiry only gets
      recomputed when a PIN is stored after a successful verify, and
      changing the setting does not recompute it for the PIN already in
      memory. I will make a duration change apply to the current PIN
      right away.<br>
      <br>
      On the PIN keyboard, good catch. That numbers-and-symbols keyboard
      is a deliberate choice, since most card PINs are numeric, but you
      are right that OpenPGP PINs can be alphanumeric, so starting away
      from letters is a fair complaint. I will make the letters easier
      to reach.<br>
      <br>
      Also a correction from my last email. I told you the send part
      wasn't working yet, but it actually does work. The mix-up was on
      my end: it defaulted to going out from a different one of my email
      accounts, so it was not showing up in the sent folder I was
      checking, and I assumed it had failed. So the whole Email
      Encrypted Message flow is working, send included. Glad it drops
      the armored block into the body cleanly on your side, so feel free
      to put the full round trip through whenever you like.<br>
      <br>
      The inline versus attachment breakdown was genuinely useful,
      especially the Thunderbird before and after. It matches what I was
      seeing: inline is the nicer experience for a desktop client that
      detects it, and a .asc attachment is actually fewer steps when the
      recipient is on iOS with PGPony. That gave me an idea I wanted to
      run by you. What if a message could carry both at once, the
      armored block inline in the body and the same ciphertext as a .asc
      attachment, so each person just uses whichever their client makes
      easy. Probably offered as a choice: inline, attachment, or both.
      The part I am unsure about is how clients handle both being
      present, so I am trying it on this very message: it is going out
      both ways, inline in the body and as a .asc attachment. Take a
      look at how the two land together on your end. Does Thunderbird
      show the inline Decrypt button and the attachment at the same
      time, and does that feel redundant or perfectly fine? You are the
      best person to tell me, so I would really like your read on it.
      And noted on Thunderbird, I will give it a look. The no iOS build
      part made me laugh.<br>
      <br>
      On the key origin, that solves it, thank you. keys.openpgp.org
      makes sense, and your point about it only releasing a verified
      address tells me the right key got confirmed there at some point.
      Since you can read my signed and encrypted messages, A0CB...DE62
      is my live key, which means the copy on pgpony.app is stale. I
      will fix the site to publish the right one and make sure the
      keyserver copy matches.<br>
      <br>
      And on the translation, no rush at all, bit by bit is perfect, and
      keeping the hardware-key terms in English wherever it reads better
      is exactly right.<br>
      <br>
      Thanks again, this kind of detail is what makes the app better.<br>=

      <br>
      NorseHorse</blockquote>
